The `init()` method in `ChromaClient` needs to allow re-initialization when a connection error or 401 occurs, and should re-apply auth headers on reconnection. Here's the fix:

```typescript
// In ChromaClient.ts, modify the init() method to support re-authentication:

async init(): Promise<void> {
  // Remove the cached _initPromise guard so reconnection can happen
  if (this._initPromise && !this._needsReconnect) {
    return this._initPromise;
  }
  this._needsReconnect = false;
  this._initPromise = this._initialize();
  return this._initPromise;
}

private async _initialize(): Promise<void> {
  // Re-apply auth headers on every init to handle token refresh
  if (this.authProvider !== undefined) {
    this.api.options.headers = {
      ...this.api.options.headers,
      ...this.authProvider.authenticate(),
    };
    await this.getUserIdentity();
  }
}

// Add a method to mark reconnection needed (call this from error handling):
private markReconnectNeeded(): void {
  this._needsReconnect = true;
  this._initPromise = undefined;
}
```

Additionally, in `ChromaFetch.ts`, when a 401 is received, the client should invalidate the init promise so the next request triggers re-authentication:

```typescript
// In ChromaFetch.ts, case 401 handling or in Collection methods,
// catch ChromaUnauthorizedError and reset init state:
case 401:
  // Signal that reconnection/re-auth is needed
  throw new ChromaUnauthorizedError(`Unauthorized - token may need refresh`);
```

And in `Collection.ts` methods (like `query`), wrap with retry logic:
```typescript
async query(params: QueryRecordsParams): Promise<MultiQueryResponse> {
  try {
    await this.client.init();
    // ... existing logic
  } catch (e) {
    if (e instanceof ChromaUnauthorizedError) {
      this.client.markReconnectNeeded();
      await this.client.init(); // retry with fresh auth
      // ... retry the request
    }
    throw e;
  }
}
```

In `rust/chroma/src/segment/manager.rs` at line 142, replace the `.unwrap()` on the mutex lock with poison-recovery or migrate to an async-safe lock. For example:

```rust
// Before (line 142):
let segments = self.segments.lock().unwrap();

// Option A: Recover from poison
let segments = self.segments.lock().unwrap_or_else(|poisoned| {
    tracing::warn!("Segment manager mutex was poisoned, recovering");
    poisoned.into_inner()
});

// Option B (preferred): Replace std::sync::Mutex with tokio::sync::RwLock
// In the struct definition:
// segments: Arc<tokio::sync::RwLock<HashMap<SegmentId, Segment>>>,
//
// At the call site:
let segments = self.segments.read().await;
```

Option B is preferred because it matches the pattern used in `local_hnsw.rs` (which wraps its `Inner` in `Arc<tokio::sync::RwLock<Inner>>`), avoids poisoning entirely, and properly supports concurrent readers without blocking.
